data collected in the Upper Laguna Madre, Texas, over a period of 9 yr from 1989 to 1997; the data set is ideally suited to testing the assumptions of the model. The data include regular measurements of above- and below-ground biomass coupled with
continuous monitoring of underwater irradiance. Although the Upper Laguna suffered from a persistent brown tide from the summer of 1990 through the spring of 1996, the model was successful in reproducing trends in the observed above- and below-ground
biomass. In particular, it captured the rapid recovery of the below-ground biomass as the brown tide bloom declined during spring 1996. Since agreement between the model and data decreases over a period of about 1 yr, some simple data-assimilation
